1.e4 {The King pawn opening. Arguably the most popular opening}
1...g6 {Black wants to play the Modern defence}
2.d4 {Grabbing the centre, White expands his pawn prowess}
2...Bg7 {The Bishop will eye the long-dark diagonal}
3.Nc3 {Adding more steel to the d5 square.}
3...d6 {Preventing White from pushing e5. If White succeeds in pushing the e5 pawn then Black will run into serious problems}
4.Be3 {Nice developing move that also adds more control over the c5 square. Black cannot play ...c5 easily.4.Bg5 looks an aggressive option but this
does lose control over the e5 square. The Bishop looks better on e3.}
4...a6!? {An interesting move. This moves prepares ...b5 followed by ...Bb7. Black intends to play ...b4 at some point to attack the
defender of the e4 pawn}
5.Qd2 {A principled move that prepares O-O-O. This moves also instills a confusion in Black's thinking...Should I play ...Nf6 or not?}
5...b5 {Black goes ahead with the plan. ...Bb7 is on the cards.The only problem with Black is that only pawn moves seem to be on the menu}
6.f3 {A prophylactic move to counter ...Bb7. White also takes advantage of the fact that Black is yet to develop the Kingside and prepares g4-h4 in the future}
6...Nd7 {Black is flexible and controls the c5 square}
7.h4 {White starts pushing the pawns as Black's Kingside is yet to be developed}
7...Ngf6 {Black has two more options. 7...h6 This move controls the g5 square and
Black is ready to meet 8.h5 with 8...g5 closing the pawn structure. 7...h6 8.Nh3!? Ngf6 9.O-O-O and White keeps his options of g4 and f4 open.
7...h5. Here Black creates a "hole" on the g5 square. Nh3-Ng5 will allow White to post a gnawing piece on the g-file. Black will have to play ...Ngf6
at some point which means the g5 square is White's "home" for the majority of the game. Morever ...h5 or ...h6 allows commital pawn moves.Black
opts for flexibility and forces White to commit aggression}
8.O-O-O {White puts the King to safety before committing on the Kingside aggression}
8...Nb6 {Black cannot play ...c5 as White's heavy artillery is in complete control of the d-file. This move vacates the d7 square for the
other Knight in case White decides to go for the Kingside onslaught. The Bishop on c8 is also active now. If White decides to develop the Knight
via the h3 route then ...Bxh3 is also a possibility to neutralise White's attack. 8...Bb7 rekindles the idea of pushing ...c5 as the Queen on d8
gets protection from the Rook. But 9.Kb1 c5?! 10.dxc5 Nxc5 11.e5!? b4 12.exf6 bxc3 13.Qxc3 Bxf6 14.Bd4!? forcing Black to give away the control of the
dark squares 14...Nd7 15.Bxf6 Nxf6 16.Ng5 and White can afford to play Bc4 soon with the Black King stuck in the centre.With the dark-squared Bishop
neutralised, Black's attack on the King on b1 is no more effective as the task of connecting the Rooks is arduous and White can regroup quickly
denying Black any counterplay.}
9.Bh6 {White wants to exchange Black's lively Bishop and weeaken the dark squares around the King. A good positional idea}
9...Bxh6 10.Qxh6*

