1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.g3 c6 4.Bg2 d5 {Neo-Grunfeld} 5.Nf3 dxc4 {Black is ready to play ...b5 and protect the extra pawn}
6.a4 {Preventing ...b5}
6...Ne4 {With an idea of playing ...Nd6 to add more protection to the pawn on c4 }
7.O-O {White goes for development}
7...Bg7 {Of course ...Nd6 is premature as White has yet not revelaed his cards and Black too develops a piece}
8.Nc3 {Challenging the Knight.Would you like to go to d6 or exchange?}
8...Nd6 {Black goes with the defense of the c4 pawn. The Knight has jumped three times since the first move. Black has an extra pawn but White
has the advantage of development.Now White needs to ascertain that he grabs more space in the centre and increases the advantage further.}
9.h3 {The g4 square is now under White's control. Black could have played ...Bg4 followed by ...Qc8 to control the h3-c8 diagonal. This would have given Black sound
positional control.White could have also gone straight for 9.e4 Bg4 10.Be3 Qc8 where the position is almost equal
9.e4 is also playable but 9...Bg4 10.Be3 Qc8 gives Black sufficient counterplay as ...Bh3 is unstoppable. Neutralising the light-squared Bishop means
Black extra pawn advantage becomes more potent.}
9...O-O 10.e4 {Now e4 makes more sense as the light square Bishop on c8 lacks space to develop on a good square. The f5 square is under White's firm grip}
10...Na6* {Black wants to plant the Knight on b4 - a hole created by White's advanced pawns. ...Nd3 is also an idea to cement the Knight in White's throat}
